#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:2
msgid "HTTP module"
msgstr "HTTP 模"

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:4
msgid ""
"`Axios <https://github.com/axios/axios>`__ is rich-feature HTTP client "
"that is widely used in dozens of applications. That’s why Nest wraps this"
" package and exposes it by default as a built-in ``HttpModule``. The "
"``HttpModule`` exports ``HttpService`` that simply exposes axios-based "
"methods to perform HTTP request, but also, transforms return types into "
"``Observables``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:11
msgid "In order to use a ``HttpService``, we need to import ``HttpModule``."
msgstr "In order to use a ``HttpService``, we need to import ``HttpModule``."

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:23
msgid ""
"info **Hint** The ``HttpModule`` is exposed from ``@nestjs/common`` "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:26
msgid ""
"Then, you can inject ``HttpService``. This class is easily accessible "
"from ``@nestjs/common`` package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:53
msgid "All methods return ``AxiosResponse`` wrapped with ``Observable`` object."
msgstr "All methods return ``AxiosResponse`` wrapped with ``Observable`` object."

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:56
msgid "Configuration"
msgstr "Configuration"

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:58
msgid ""
"`Axios <https://github.com/axios/axios>`__ gives a bunch of options that "
"you may take advantage of to make your ``HttpService`` even more "
"powerful. Read more about them `here <https://github.com/axios/axios"
"#request-config>`__. To configure underlying library instance, use "
"``register()`` method of ``HttpModule``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:78
msgid "All these properties will be passed down to the **axios** constructor."
msgstr "All these properties will be passed down to the **axios** constructor."

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:81
msgid "Async configuration"
msgstr "Async configuration"

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:83
msgid ""
"Quite often you might want to asynchronously pass your module options "
"instead of passing them beforehand. In such case, use ``registerAsync()``"
" method, that provides a couple of various ways to deal with async data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:88
msgid "First possible approach is to use a factory function:"
msgstr "First possible approach is to use a factory function:"

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:99
msgid ""
"Obviously, our factory behaves like every other one (might be ``async`` "
"and is able to inject dependencies through ``inject``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:113
msgid "Alternatively, you are able to use class instead of a factory."
msgstr "Alternatively, you are able to use class instead of a factory."

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:121
msgid ""
"Above construction will instantiate ``HttpConfigService`` inside "
"``HttpModule`` and will leverage it to create options object. The "
"``HttpConfigService`` has to implement ``HttpOptionsFactory`` interface."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:137
msgid ""
"In order to prevent the creation of ``HttpConfigService`` inside "
"``HttpModule`` and use a provider imported from a different module, you "
"can use the ``useExisting`` syntax."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/techniques/http-module.rst:148
msgid ""
"It works the same as ``useClass`` with one critical difference - "
"``HttpModule`` will lookup imported modules to reuse already created "
"``ConfigService``, instead of instantiating it on its own."
msgstr ""

